{"why_md_fmt":" Higher rates of unemployment in an area are likely to have a negative effect on health in that area. Areas with higher rates of unemployment are most affected by:

- Lower lifetime income
- Lack of employer-provided health care
- Reduced human and societal capital

- Higher rates of poverty
- Higher rates of stress and physiological poor health
- Reduced life expectancy
- Reduced quality of life
","references":[{"date":"Mar 2013","publisher":"Robert Wood Johnson Foundation","link":"http://www.rwjf.org/content/dam/farm/reports/issue_briefs/2013/rwjf403360","title":"How Does Employment - or Unemployment - Affect Health?"},{"date":"July 2013","publisher":"Urban Institute","link":"http://www.urban.org/uploadedpdf/412887-consequences-of-long-term-unemployment.pdf","title":"Consequences of Long-Term Unemployment"},{"date":"1999","publisher":"International Journal of Health Services","link":"http://individual.utoronto.ca/cmuntaner/publications/1990/1999MuntanerIntJHealthServ1.pdf","title":"Social Inequalities and Their Effect on Health and Well-Being"}],"stats":{"average":0.04193,"std_dev":0.0266,"better_sign":-1},"score_md_fmt":"In **{boundary}**, **{value}** of people are searching for employment but unable to find a job, versus **{average}** in {domain}. fields.params:
{"why_md_fmt":"Higher rates of high school graduation indicate a higher level of educational attainment. Populations with higher levels of educational attainment can be expected to report better health than populations with lower levels of educational attainment. This is because a well educated population is more likely to:

- Be financially stable
- Avoid certain risk factors

Therefore, areas where more of the population has graduated high school are more likely to experience:

- Lower rates of poverty
- Higher life expectancy
- Lower rates of injury and illness
- A higher quality of life
","references":[{"date":"Mar 2007","publisher":"National Bureau of Economic Research","link":"http://www.nber.org/digest/mar07/w12352.html","title":"The Effects of Education on Health"}],"stats":{"average":0.861836,"std_dev":0.096739,"better_sign":1},"score_md_fmt":"In **{boundary}**, **{value}** of people 25 and older have graduated from high school, versus **{average}** in {domain}.
